In C#, the `/// <summary>` and `///<param...>` are XML comments that are used for documenting code. These comments provide a way to describe the purpose, functionality, and parameters of a method, property, class, or other code elements. These XML comments can then be processed by tools like IntelliSense, which provides contextual help and documentation within Visual Studio or other IDEs.

Here's a breakdown of each:

- `/// <summary>`: This XML comment is used to provide a summary or brief description of the code element. It is commonly placed just above a method, class, or other code element and can be used to explain its purpose, expected behavior, or any other relevant details.

- `///<param...>`: This XML comment is used to provide detailed information about the parameters of a method or constructor. It is written as a separate comment line for each parameter, starting with `///<param name="parameterName">` followed by the description of the parameter.

Here's an example to illustrate their usage:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Adds two numbers and returns the result.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="a">The first number.</param>
/// <param name="b">The second number.</param>
/// <returns>The sum of the two numbers.</returns>
public int Add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}
```

In the example above, the `<summary>` comment provides a brief description of the `Add` method, and the `<param>` tags are used to describe the purpose of each parameter. These comments help document the code, making it easier for other developers to understand and use the code later on.
